\layout Section

Subdivision schemes
\layout Standard

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $b>1$
\end_inset 

 be an integer, given two integers 
\begin_inset Formula $k,j$
\end_inset 

, the number 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j,k}=k/b^{j}$
\end_inset 

 is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $b-$
\end_inset 

adic (of depth 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

).
 For a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $b-$
\end_inset 

adic numbers form a regularly spaced set of nodes.
 For a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset 

, given some data 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ y_{J,k}\right\} _{k\in \Z }$
\end_inset 

, we want a smooth function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x_{J,k}\right)=y_{J,k}\, \forall k\in \Z $
\end_inset 

.
 Starting with (
\begin_inset Formula $y_{J,k}$
\end_inset 

) and using the formula 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
y_{j+1,l}=\sum _{k\in \Z }\gamma _{bk-l}y_{j,k}\label{basicsubdivision}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 for some array 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma $
\end_inset 

, we get values 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,k}$
\end_inset 

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $j>J$
\end_inset 

 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $b-$
\end_inset 

adic numbers form a dense set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\R $
\end_inset 

, there is at most one continuous function such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x_{j,k}\right)=y_{j,k}$
\end_inset 

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in \Z ,j>J$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

A subdivision scheme is 
\shape italic 
interpolatory
\shape default 
 and satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x_{J,k}\right)=y_{J,k}$
\end_inset 

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma _{bk}=0\, \forall k\in \Z $
\end_inset 

 except for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma _{0}=1$
\end_inset 

.
 We say that a subdivision scheme is
\shape italic 
 stationary
\shape default 
 if the array 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma $
\end_inset 

 is constant (does not depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

).
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma $
\end_inset 

 does not depend explicitly on 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset 

 but rather on 
\begin_inset Formula $bk-l$
\end_inset 

 the scheme is 
\shape italic 
translation invariant
\shape default 
 or 
\shape italic 
homogeneous
\shape default 
.
 A subdivision scheme is 
\begin_inset Formula $2N-$
\end_inset 

point if 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma _{l}=0$
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $|l|\geq Nb$
\end_inset 

.
 The fundamental function of an interpolatory 
\begin_inset Formula $2N-$
\end_inset 

point 
\begin_inset Formula $b-$
\end_inset 

adic scheme has initial data 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0,0}=1$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0,k}=0$
\end_inset 

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\neq 0$
\end_inset 

; it has a compact support of 
\begin_inset Formula $[-(Nb-1)/(b-1),(Nb-1)/(b-1)]$
\end_inset 

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $[1-2N,2N-1]$
\end_inset 

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $b=2$
\end_inset 

).
 
\layout Standard

For 
\begin_inset Formula $N=1,2,3,...$
\end_inset 

 there are corresponding interpolatory 
\begin_inset Formula $2N-$
\end_inset 

point interpolatory Deslauriers-Dubuc subdivision schemes built from the
 midpoint evaluation of Lagrange polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $2N-1$
\end_inset 

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $b=2$
\end_inset 

 (dyadic case), the 
\begin_inset Formula $4-$
\end_inset 

point Deslauriers-Dubuc scheme can be defined with the array 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma ^{DD2}$
\end_inset 

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma _{0}^{DD2}=1,\, $
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula $\gamma _{1}^{DD2}=\gamma _{-1}^{DD2}=-9/16,\, $
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula $\gamma _{3}^{DD2}=\gamma _{-3}^{DD2}=-1/16$
\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma _{k}^{DD2}=0$
\end_inset 

 otherwise; for 
\begin_inset Formula $b=4$
\end_inset 

 (tetradic case), the scheme is defined with the array 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma ^{DD4}$
\end_inset 

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma _{2k}^{DD4}=\gamma _{k}^{DD2}\, \forall k\in \Z ,\, $
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma _{-1}^{DD4}=\gamma _{1}^{DD4}=105/128,\, $
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula $\gamma _{-3}^{DD4}=\gamma _{-3}^{DD4}=35/128,\, $
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula $\gamma _{-5}^{DD4}=\gamma _{5}^{DD4}=-7/128,\, $
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula $\gamma _{-7}^{DD4}=\gamma _{7}^{DD4}=-5/128,\, $
\end_inset 

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma _{k}^{DD2}=0$
\end_inset 

 otherwise.
 
\layout Standard

Because 
\begin_inset Formula $4-$
\end_inset 

point Deslauriers-Dubuc schemes are derived from cubic Lagrange polynomials,
 they reproduce cubic polynomials, that is, if the initial data 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,k}$
\end_inset 

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,k}=p\left(x_{j,k}\right)\, \forall k\in \Z $
\end_inset 

 for some cubic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

 then the interpolation function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

 is this same cubic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f=p$
\end_inset 

.
 The two cases presented above (
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma ^{DD2}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma ^{DD4}$
\end_inset 

) reproduce cubic polynomials and they both converge to differentiable (
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset 

) interpolation functions.
 Because we later borrow from these two subdivision schemes, we give explicit
 algorithms for both schemes.
