\end_inset 

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert P^{j+1}(z)\right\Vert _{sup}\leq \lambda _{HR}\left\Vert P^{j}(z)\right\Vert _{sup}$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Lemma


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{enoughlemma}

\end_inset 

A HRS scheme given by the symbol equation 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{j+1}(z)=\Phi _{1}(z)P^{j}\left(z^{2}\right)+\Phi _{2}(z)P^{j}\left(-z^{2}\right)$
\end_inset 

 converges uniformly to zero for all bounded initial values if 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda _{HR}<1$
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda _{HR}$
\end_inset 

 is as in equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{lemmaenough}

\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

We are now ready to prove the following theorem.
\layout Theorem


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{maintheorem}

\end_inset 

For 
\begin_inset Formula $-25/56<\alpha <15/32$
\end_inset 

, the HRS schemes given by equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{gammas}

\end_inset 

 (algorithm 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{4pointhrssalgo}

\end_inset 

) are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Proof

The symbol of the HRS scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $dD_{j,k}=dD_{j,k}^{1}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $dH_{1}$
\end_inset 

 is given by (see equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{dH}

\end_inset 

) 
\begin_inset Formula \[
dH_{1}^{j+1}(z)=2\left(\frac{z}{1+z}\right)^{2}\Gamma _{1}(z)dH_{1}^{j}\left(z^{2}\right)+2\left(\frac{-z(1-z)}{1+z^{2}}\right)^{2}\Gamma _{2}(z)dH_{1}^{j}\left(-z^{2}\right)\]

\end_inset 

By theorem 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{DynTheorem}

\end_inset 

, it is enough to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $dD_{j,k}$
\end_inset 

 converges uniformly to zero for all bounded initial data.
 However, using lemma 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{enoughlemma}

\end_inset 

, we know that it is sufficient to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda _{HR}<1$
\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi _{1}(z)=2z^{2}\Gamma _{1}(z)/\left(1+z\right)^{2}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi _{2}(z)=2z^{2}(1-z)^{2}\Gamma _{2}(z)/\left(1+z^{2}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset 

.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\lambda _{1} & = & \frac{5+2\left|4\alpha +1\right|+2\left|7-8\alpha \right|+2\left|5+12\alpha \right|+\left|32\alpha +5\right|+\left|5-8\alpha \right|+\left|24\alpha -7\right|}{64}\\
\lambda _{2} & = & \frac{5+2\left|4\alpha +1\right|+2\left|3+8\alpha \right|+2\left|1-4\alpha \right|+\left|21-32\alpha \right|+\left|1+8\alpha \right|+\left|24\alpha +11\right|}{64}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset 

Hence, for 
\begin_inset Formula $-25/56<\alpha <15/32$
\end_inset 

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda _{1}<1$
\end_inset 

, whereas for 
\begin_inset Formula $-7/12<\alpha <5/8$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda _{2}<1$
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda _{HR}=\max \left\{ \lambda _{1},\lambda _{2}\right\} <1$
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $-25/56<\alpha <15/32$
\end_inset 

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $-\sim 0.45<\alpha <\sim 0.47$
\end_inset 

 (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{FigLambdas}

\end_inset 

).
 
\layout Standard

